node.text:
Sexism with @tova_leigh ☝️

"A few weeks ago I asked you to share with me examples of sexism & casual sexism in your lives. I was inundated by thousands of messages from, mainly women, who shared from their everyday lives examples of sexism and how it affects them. It’s been on my mind ever since... Sexism affects everyone, including men... But the reason I wanted to make this video is because there is a very strong link between sexism and gender inequality and I truly believe that until we break these stereotypes we’ve all been brainwashed to believe, we will struggle to achieve true equality."

Video by @tova_leigh, shared with permission. For more videos like these head over to Tova's page 🙌

6-year-old Kiara surprises Awkwafina and Kelly Marie Tran with a special interview for their new film Disney's Raya and The Last Dragon.

We loved working with Disney for this and would like to invite you to join us for a special LIVE panel with Disney's Raya and The Last Dragon's incredible female filmmakers:

Producer: Osnat Shurer (also worked on Moana)
Screenwriter: Adele Lim (Crazy Rich Asians)
Head of Story: Fawn Veerasunthorn (Frozen)
Modeler: Liza Rhea (Ralph Breaks the Internet)

We will also be joined by The Female Lead's Founder Edwina Dunn, two young fans (who will be asking questions) 14-year-old Inspiring Vanessa @inspiringvanessa, 6-year-old Kiara who is in this video (thanks to her parents @mrsnydcrawford, @ryanashcrawford) and our wonderful moderator, Katie Carroll!

Also, stay tuned for a special message from the voice cast Awkwafina and Kelly Marie Tran and remember you can watch Raya and The Last Dragon from tomorrow on Disney+ Premier Access!

We'll be going LIVE at 6PM GMT 😁

@lottiedrynan: "If a pair of shoes don’t fit you, you don’t blame your feet, you find a pair shoes that do fit. So when a dress, or a pair of shorts don’t fit, why blame your body? Your body was not made to fit into clothes, clothes are made to fit onto your body. And if they don’t, then they are not the clothes for you. 

Absolutely loved this analogy by @storysellerscomics as thought it was a light hearted way to show how much worth we put onto our dress size and it’s something I wish I read a few years ago.

Although I have to say I read the absolute shit show of the comments section and it honestly it only made me want to make this more. For all those saying “STOP PROMOTING OBESITY, U ARE KILLING PEOPLE, UR A MURDERER” - honestly the level of extremity and fatphobia that a cute analogy can be taken to is just WILD. Secondly, for those saying “yeah but you can control the size of your body not your feet” this is in many cases incorrect - there are so many factors that impact our body and weight/measurements. You cannot measure health by dress size. Also it really is just a cute analogy and if something on the internet doesn’t help or resonate with you, that really is okay, just move the hell on and carry on as you were 😅"

Video and words by @lottiedrynan

The 3x gold medalist @beccameyers20 said that she's dropping out of the Tokyo Paralympics. The swimmer, who is deaf-blind, made the decision as a result of the U.S. Olympic & Paralympic Committee refusing her request to bring her personal care assistant with her. 

"I'm angry, I'm disappointed, but most of all, I'm sad to not be representing my country."

Knowing them benefits all involved. A non exhaustive'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says '3 Charlie Knight [they/them] @CKnightWrites 1. Outside of emergencies, there is no reason for you to touch someone's wheelchair unless asked. If we're in the way, treat us like you would anyone else and say "excuse me.' it looks like we're stuck, treat us like you would anyone else and ask if we need help. Don't touch. Charlie Knight [thy/them] @CKnightWrites (Cont) can't emphasize how important this is. A wheelchair is an extension of our bodies. you wouldn't lift and move an abled person without asking, don't push a wheelchair. Grabbing my chair It's assault. grabbing me.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Charlie Knight [.hey/them] @CKnightWrites 2. Unless you woulo otherwise be screaming to be heard, there is no reason to bend down or kneel to speak to someone in a wheelchair. Think about it. You don't bend to be eye level with abled adults. You do bend down to speak to children, though. Don't infantalize us. us'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Charlie Knight [thy/them] them] @CKnightWrites 3. Don't speak over or about us. Meaning, don't look at my husband and ask "do they need help getting in?" when I'm right there. This is another infantilizing move and it's horribly disrespectful.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'Charlie Knight [they/them] @CKnightWrites 4. Do not assume that someone in a wheelchair isn't ambulatory (mobile). Sometimes, a person using a wheelchair can walk and will. This should not be a shock and is not an opportunity for questions about our disability.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Charlie Knight [thy/them] @CKnightWrites 5. Jnless we're in a setting where it would be appropriate (you're our doctor and we're in the oafce hospital, or you're paying us at an event to speak about it) there is no opportunity for you to ask questions about our disability. That's just rude.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Charlie Knight [thy/them] @CKnightWrites 6. The above goes for your children, too. Disabled people are not a learning opportunity do not turn us into one by telling kids that staring/pointing is bad but they can ask us questions. No, they cant. t's still rude, and it's not our responsibility to to educate your kids.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be an image of one or more people and text that says 'Charlie Knight [they/them] @CKnightWrites 7. Don't move our wheelchairs after we've transferred out either, not until we say it's okay and know where it's going. If transfer out of my chair at restaurant and the waitstaff whisks my chair away, they've effectively taken my legs and hidden them. No, thank you. Charlie Knight [.hey/them] @CKnightWrites 8. Don't go out of your way to avoid saying things like "talk a walk." We're pretty likely to express things that way too, and "take a roll" as a cutesy alternative is not as funny as you think.'.

Photo by The Female Lead on July 20, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of one or more people and text that says 'Charlie Knight [they/them] @CKnightWrites 9. Use the word "disabled. It's not a dirty word. Alternatives like 'differently abled" are infantalizing and gross, and terms like "handicapped" and "crippled" are both outdated and (often) offensive. Disabled. Get comfy with it. Charlie Knight [thy/them] @CKnightWrites 10 Don't say things like "wheelchair bound" or "confined to a wheelchair." Mobility aids like wheelchairs give us our freedom; they're a good thing, not a trap.'.

node.text:
@tova_leigh: Examples of the type of comments I got on my recent nailed it video (with the white bedsheet). Don't worry, I'm not offended! I am sharing because I want to talk about it. 90% of these comments are from men. With all due respect to the lovely men who follow my channels, I don't really care what guys think about my body. Gone are the days that I live my life through a male gaze and if I'm being totally honest - men have discussed women's bodies enough throughout history it's really time we moved on from that. 10% of these comments however came from women and this is what I'd like to focus on. While the urge to get upset is totally there, I have managed to turn my anger into empathy and I will tell you why. That loathing, that disgusting feeling of can't even bare to see someone else's body usually comes from a place of SELF loathing. It's most likely that the women who get angry just by seeing my body feel that way because it reminds them of their own bodies which they hate because they don't match up to society's beauty standards for women. Maybe it's the type of body they are so petrified of having? After all, we've been brought up to be SCARED of our own bodies. Of how they might change, how they age and what that means and in case you did not know - fear is one side of the coin. The other side is hate. We are afraid, so we hate... even ourselves. And I find that sad. So no, I'm not angry, or hurt. I just wish I could reassure those women who took offence from my saggy boobs and soft stomach that they don't need to worry so much. To be honest, I wish we could stop talking about women's bodies altogether cuz life's too short... BUT I will continue showing up with all my wobbly bits and have these conversations for the sake of those who need to see that it really doesn't matter. Ladies, I walked around in a bedsheet that looked like a nappy with my boobs practically hanging out and I posted it on the internet for millions to see. And guess what happened? nothing. The earth did not open up and swallow me whole, my husband did not leave me, my life did not end... it literally was ok. Less hate, more living, that's all I gotta say. ❤️

#feminism
